ompelling tale, Acts of Occupation throws new light on a transformative period in the history of Canadian Arctic policy and provides much-needed historical context for contemporary debates on northern sovereignty.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArctic regions -- Discovery and exploration. 0aCanada -- Boundaries -- Arctic regions. 0aCanada -- Foreign relations -- 1914-1945. 0aCanada, Northern -- Discovery and exploration. 0aCanada, Northern -- Politics and government. 0aJurisdiction, Territorial -- Canada. 7aHISTORY / Polar Regions.2bisacsh1 aNoakes, Jeff, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010z978311127414008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010z978311127721908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077481869840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774818698423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774818698/original  a978-3-11-127414-0  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010c2010d2011  a978-3-11-127721-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010c2010d2011  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000c2013d2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles